      "writtenOn": "2015-12-02T20:41:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "it looks like you are calling connected() from multiple threads, and the function reads a member field (mFdWatch) without any locking or memory barriers. I smell a race condition here.",
      "revId": "a89a841b0a7a629b60927ff7040e6fa278d37b6f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5b1deb19_458654cc",
        "filename": "android/wear-agent/WearAgent.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 256,
      "author": {
        "id": 1080076
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-12-02T23:57:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "connected() only reads a single pointer. on x86 pointer-sized read is atomic",
      "parentUuid": "db339bd5_4ae05319",
      "revId": "a89a841b0a7a629b60927ff7040e6fa278d37b6f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9b2da379_c86c4fa2",
        "filename": "android/wear-agent/WearAgent.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 256,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-12-03T09:57:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "even if the read is atomic, you need memory barriers to ensure proper ordering, because you are going to use other members of the same object after. This thing is always tricky!.\n\nActually, it might be that on Intel CPUs, the memory order semantics guarantee that this specific code path always work, but this is not portable in general, and anything subtle like this should be tagged with a big comment explaining why it\u0027s ok to use in this specific context.",
      "parentUuid": "5b1deb19_458654cc",
      "revId": "a89a841b0a7a629b60927ff7040e6fa278d37b6f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a0f23453_a0627ae7",
        "filename": "android/wear-agent/WearAgent.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 280,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-12-02T20:41:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "ow, that\u0027s dangerous. Loopers and their data structures are single-thread entities, i.e. they are not designed from being invoked from different threads. This call is modifying another thread\u0027s looper, which is a potential data race / random crash source. You really need better synchronization here.\n\nI looks like what you need is a socketpair() that allows you to send one byte from this thread, and have a fdWatch() on the main thread that triggers a callback when it receives it. We don\u0027t have a helper class to do this in android/base/, it might be useful to add one.\n\nSee socket_pair() in android/utils/sockets.c if that can help. Another alternative is to add a Looper::Event class to android/base/Looper.h but that requires more work.",
      "revId": "a89a841b0a7a629b60927ff7040e6fa278d37b6f",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
